/*  Logic :

1. If the asteroid is moving right (positive):

   * It cannot collide with any previous asteroid.
   * Store it in the stack.

2. If the asteroid is moving left (negative) :

   * Compare it with the top of the stack **only if the top is moving right** (because only then can a collision happen).
   * If the top positive asteroid is **smaller**, it gets destroyed. Keep checking the next asteroid in the stack.
   * If the top positive asteroid is **the same size**, both asteroids are destroyed.
   * If the top positive asteroid is **larger**, the current negative asteroid is destroyed.
   * If the stack becomes empty, or the top of the stack is also moving left (negative), there is no collision, so the current negative asteroid survives and is added to the stack.

At the end, the stack contains all the asteroids that survive after all collisions.
*/

class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> asteroidCollision(vector<int>& asteroids) {
        int n = asteroids.size();
        vector<int> st; // Stack to store surviving asteroids

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {

            // Positive asteroids can never collide with previous ones
            if (asteroids[i] > 0) {
                st.push_back(asteroids[i]);
            } else { // Current asteroid is moving left

                // Destroy all smaller positive asteroids
                while (!st.empty() && st.back() > 0 &&
                       st.back() < abs(asteroids[i]))
                    st.pop_back();

                // Equal-sized asteroids destroy each other
                if (!st.empty() && st.back() == abs(asteroids[i]))
                    st.pop_back();

                // No collision possible, so current asteroid survives
                else if (st.empty() || st.back() < 0)
                    st.push_back(asteroids[i]);

                // Else: top positive asteroid is larger,
                // so current negative asteroid is destroyed
            }
        }

        return st;
    }
};
